## Common LaTeX Patterns in Economics Papers

### Tables
```latex
\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Descriptive title}
\label{tab:label}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
...
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
```

### Figures
```latex
\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{filename}
\caption{Descriptive caption}
\label{fig:label}
\end{figure}
```

### Equations
```latex
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:label}
y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \epsilon
\end{equation}
```

### Cross-references
- Tables: `Table~\ref{tab:label}`
- Figures: `Figure~\ref{fig:label}`
- Equations: `Equation~\eqref{eq:label}` or just `\eqref{eq:label}`
- Sections: `Section~\ref{sec:label}`

Note: The `~` creates a non-breaking space to prevent line breaks between "Table" and the number.

